{{about|the medieval historian|the actor|Alex Wolff}} {{Infobox person | name = Alex Woolf | image = | alt = | caption = | birth_date = {{birth year and age|1963}} | birth_place = | death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) --> | death_place = | nationality = [[British people|British]] | other_names = | known_for = | occupation = Medieval historian | notable_works = New Edinburgh History of Scotland
}} '''Alex Woolf''', {{Post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|FSAs}} (born 1963) is a British [[medieval]] [[historian]] and academic. He specialises in the history of the [[British Isles]] and [[Scandinavia]] in the [[Early Middle Ages]], especially in relation to the peoples of [[Wales]] and [[Scotland]]. He is a [[Senior Lecturer]] at the [[University of St Andrews]].<ref name="St Andrews bio">{{cite web|title=Dr Alex Woolf|url=https://www.st-andrews.ac.uk/history/staff/alexwoolf.html|website=School of History|publisher=University of St Andrews|accessdate=30 September 2017}}</ref>
He is author of volume two in the ''New Edinburgh History of Scotland'', covering the period between 789 and 1070. For this he won the 2008 [[Saltire Society]] award for "history book of the year".
==Academic career== In 1995, Woolf was appointed a [[lecturer]] in archaeology at the [[University of Wales, Lampeter]].<ref name="Spotlight">{{cite web|title=Spotlight on Alex Woolf|url=https://standrewsschoolofhistory.wordpress.com/2013/02/01/spotlight-on-alex-woolf/|website=St Andrews School of History|publisher=University of St Andrews|accessdate=30 September 2017|date=1 February 2013}}</ref> From 1997 to 2001, he was a lecturer in Celtic and early Scottish history and culture at the [[University of Edinburgh]].<ref name="St Andrews bio" /> In 2001, he moved to the [[University of St Andrews]] as a lecturer in history:<ref name="St Andrews bio" /><ref name="Spotlight" /> he was later promoted to [[senior lecturer]].<ref name="St Andrews bio" />
==Selected works== * "Caedualla Rex Brettonum and the passing of the Old North", ''Northern History'' 41.1, 1-20 (2004) * {{cite book |editor1-last=Woolf |editor1-first=Alex |title=Landscape and environment in Dark Age Scotland |date=2006 |publisher=The Committee for Dark Age Studies, University of St Andrews |location=St Andrews |isbn=978-0951257364}} * "Dun Nechtain, Fortriu and the Geography of the Picts"; ''Scottish Historical Review'' 2006 ; 85(2): 182-201 * "The expulsion of the Irish from Dyfed"; ''Ireland and Wales in the Middle Ages''; Karen Jankulak, Jonathan Wooding (ed); Four Courts Press 2007; 102-115 * {{cite book |last1=Woolf |first1=Alex |title=From Pictland to Alba, 789-1070 (New Edinburgh History of Scotland) |date=2007 |publisher=Edinburgh University Press |location=Edinburgh |isbn=978-0748612345}} * {{cite book |editor1-last=Woolf |editor1-first=Alex |title=Scandinavian Scotland, 20 Years After: the proceedings of a day conference held on 19 February 2007 |date=2009 |publisher=University of St. Andrews, Committee for Dark Age Studies |location=St Andrews |isbn=978-0951257371}} * {{cite book |last1=Woolf |first1=Alex |title=A short history of the Celts |date=2012 |publisher=I.B. Tauris |location=London |isbn=978-1848857957}} * {{cite book |editor1-last=Woolf |editor1-first=Alex |title=Beyond the Gododdin: dark age Scotland in medieval Wales: the Proceedings of a Day Conference Held on 19 February 2005 |date=2005 |publisher=University of St. Andrews, Committee for Dark Age Studies |location=St Andrews |isbn=978-0951257388}}
