===Michelangelo bronzes===

In 2015, the museum displayed two bronze statues (the [[Rothschild Bronzes]]) that it believed to be the work of Italian [[Renaissance]] artist [[Michaelangelo]]. If true, they would be the only known surviving bronze sculptures by the artist.  The pair of statues depict naked, apparently drunk, men riding [[panthera|panthers]].  Art historian [[Paul Joannides (art historian)|Paul Joannides]] connected the statues to a drawing in the [[Musée Fabre]] by an apprentice of Michelangelo depicting the same subject in the same pose.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fitzmuseum.cam.ac.uk/news/archive/article.html?5006 |title=The Fitzwilliam Museum : Home |publisher=Fitzmuseum.cam.ac.uk |date= |accessdate=2015-08-29 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150905162521/http://www.fitzmuseum.cam.ac.uk/news/archive/article.html?5006 |archivedate=5 September 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Mark Brown |url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2015/feb/02/michelangelo-bronzes-sculptures-fitzwilliam-museum-cambridge |title=Michelangelo's bronze panther-riders revealed after 'Renaissance whodunnit' &#124; Art and design |publisher=The Guardian |date=2015-01-30 |accessdate=2015-08-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/prospero/2015/02/michelangelo |title=Michelangelo: The story of the bronze riders |publisher=The Economist |date=2015-02-02 |accessdate=2015-08-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pri.org/stories/2015-02-03/nude-drunk-and-riding-panthers-michelangelos-lost-masterpiece-discovered |title=Nude, drunk and riding on panthers: Michelangelo's lost masterpiece discovered &#124; Public Radio International |publisher=Pri.org |date=2015-02-03 |accessdate=2015-08-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-cambridgeshire-31085336 |title=Bronze sculptures 'may be by Michelangelo' - BBC News |publisher=Bbc.com |date= |accessdate=2015-08-29}}</ref>

===Losses===
On 25 January 2006, a visitor tripped which resulted in three huge oriental porcelain vases being shattered and requiring painstaking reconstruction.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fitzmuseum.cam.ac.uk/gallery/chinesevases/ |title=The Fitzwilliam Museum : Chinese Vases Home |publisher=Fitzmuseum.cam.ac.uk |date=2006-01-25 |accessdate=2014-07-15}}</ref> The damaged [[Qing Dynasty]] vases had been displayed since 1948.<ref>{{cite web |title=Kangxi Chinese vases conservation |url=https://www.fitzmuseum.cam.ac.uk/research/chinesevases |publisher=Fitzwilliam Museum}}</ref> In April 2006, the man was arrested on charges of causing [[criminal damage]]. but charges  were dropped.[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/cambridgeshire/5098362.stm] The vases ware restored and put back on display.

At around 19:30 BST on 13 April 2012, 18 valuable and culturally significant Chinese works of art were stolen.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-cambridgeshire-17758686 | work=BBC News | title=Fitzwilliam Museum theft: Chinese jade art 'worth millions' | date=18 April 2012}}</ref> The burglars were sentenced to a combined 18 years in jail.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://cambridgetab.co.uk/news/fitz-robbers-get-18-years |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121003092204/http://cambridgetab.co.uk/news/fitz-robbers-get-18-years |dead-url=yes |archive-date=3 October 2012 |title=Fitz Robbers get 18 years &#124; The Tab Cambridge |publisher=Cambridgetab.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2014-07-15 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>

