{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2014}}
{{infobox organization | name = The Ribbon International | image = File:The Ribbon International.jpg | map = The Ribbon Route.jpg | map_caption = Route of the Ribbon event held in Washington, D.C., on August 4, 1985 | image_size = 250px | formation = {{start date|1983|04|11}}{{sfn|Pershing|1996|p=98}} | founder = Justine Merritt | extinction = <!--e.g. use {{end date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}}--> | status = United Nations [[non-governmental organization]] | purpose = [[Anti-nuclear]] protest | website = {{url|http://www.theribboninternational.org/}} }} '''The Ribbon International''' is a United Nations Non-Governmental Organization that created a large decorated cloth promoting [[nuclear disarmament]] and care and protection of the earth. In an event held on August 4, 1985, panels were connected in an {{convert|18|mi|km}} long strip stretching from [[the Pentagon]] into Washington D.C. The event was covered in the film ''The Ribbon Starts Here'' by [[Nigel Noble]] (1988). Individual sections of the Ribbon are exhibited internationally. In 1991, The Ribbon International became a United Nations Non Governmental Organization.<ref name="The Ribbon International">{{cite web | title = The Ribbon International | work = UN NGO Directory | publisher = United Nations | url = http://esango.un.org/civilsociety/showProfileDetail.do?method=showProfileDetails&profileCode=610092 | accessdate = 2014-06-27}}</ref> Ribbon events can be held for special designated days such as the [[International Day of Peace]] (September 21), [[Earth Day]] (April 21), special prayer days or other events.<ref name="Peppers 14">{{cite journal | last = Peppers | first = Michelle | title = The Ribbon is an Art Project Promoting Peace | journal = International Teacher | date = June 2011 | page = 14 | issn = 1396-8580}}</ref> Panels from the Ribbon were displayed at the [[United Nations Decade for Women]] international conference in [[Nairobi]] in 1985, and others were used by members of Women for a Meaningful Summit at their demonstration at the [[Geneva Summit (1985)]]. Ribbons were used at peace demonstrations at the [[Nevada Nuclear Test Site]], and the Horse Creek Missile Silo near [[Cheyenne, Wyoming]], and the [[Great Peace March for Global Nuclear Disarmament]] in 1986.{{sfn|Pershing|1996|p=264}}
== Planning == [[File:Justines Ribbon.jpg|thumb|Merritt's first Ribbon panel is embroidered with the names of people she loved.]]
The Ribbon International was created in 1982 as a [[Anti-nuclear protests|protest against nuclear war]] by Justine Merritt (1924–2009)<ref>{{cite web | last = Merritt | first = Justine | title = Sowing Seeds | url = http://justinemerritt.net/ | accessdate = 2014-02-25}}</ref>
Following a trip to the [[Hiroshima Peace Memorial Museum]] in [[Hiroshima]], Japan, in 1975, Merritt conceived the idea of wrapping [[the Pentagon]] with a mile of ribbon to recall (in Merritt's words) "that we love the earth and its people," which is analogous with tying a string around one's finger to remember something.<ref name="Grogan">{{cite journal | last = Grogan | first = David | title = A Pentagon Ribbon for Peace | url = http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20091229,00.html | journal = People Magazine | date = July 8, 1985 | volume = 24 | issue = 2 | accessdate = 2014-06-28}}</ref>{{sfn|Pershing|1996|p=80}} The event took place on August 4, 1985,<ref>{{cite journal | last = Kingson | first = Jennifer A. | title = Ring Around the Pentagon: A Nuclear Frieze | url = http://www.thecrimson.com/article/1985/2/8/ring-around-the-pentagon-a-nuclear/ | journal = The Harvard Crimson | date = February 8, 1985 | accessdate = 2014-06-28}}</ref><ref name="Pentagon Ceremony">{{cite journal | title = Pentagon Ceremony Aug. 4 Peace Ribbons in Oklahoma Called In | url = http://newsok.com/pentagon-ceremony-aug.-4-peace-ribbons-in-oklahoma-called-in/article/2115461 | journal = The Oklahoman: NewsOK| date = July 20, 1985 | accessdate = 2014-06-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last = Kampel | first = Stewart | title = A 'Ribbon' For Peace Unfurled On L.I. | url = https://www.nytimes.com/1985/03/03/nyregion/a-ribbon-for-peace-unfurled-on-li.html | journal = New York Times | date = March 3, 1985 | accessdate = 2014-06-28}}</ref> the 40th anniversary of the [[atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki]].{{sfn|Pershing|1996|p=1}}
[[File:Justine Merritt.jpg|thumb|left|Justine Merritt founded the project.]]
The Ribbon was made in the three years leading up to the Pentagon event from hundreds of panels created by local groups co-ordinated nationally by Mary Frances Jaster of Denver with state co-ordinators. Each {{convert|36|by|18|in|cm}} panel used embroidery, quilting, painting and other techniques. The makers were invited to convey their thoughts and emotions in the panels, with their story on the back.
Friends, relatives, places of worship, and other organizations helped spread Merritt's idea throughout the United States and around the world. Local newsletters and arts and crafts magazines such as ''Fibre Art'', ''Handwoven'', and ''Quilter's Newsletter Magazine'' helped publicize the project.<ref name= "Wilcox">{{cite journal | last = Wilcox | first = Don | title = Peace Ribbon Wraps Washington In Largest Collaborative Craft Event In American History | journal = The Craft Report | date = October 1985 | page = 10}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last = Fanning | first = Robbie | title = Fibre Artist Hopes to Wrap Pentagon in Long Embroidered Ribbon That Transforms Ugly Fear Into Concrete Beauty | journal = The Craft Report | date = December 1983 | page = 3}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | title = Sew To Speak Is Theme For Ribbon For Peace | journal = Quilters Newsletter Magazine | date = November–December 1984 | page = 9}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal| last=Levin| first=Adam | title= Works From the Heart: Home Sewers Unite To Tie Up the Pentagon | journal=Sews News| volume=June 1985}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last = Fanning | first = Robbie | title = After the Ribbon | journal = Threads Magazine | date = December 1985 – January 1986 | pages = 12, 14}}</ref> Stories leading up to the Pentagon event appeared in over 2,500 publications, including local newspapers<ref>{{cite journal | last = Kernan | first = Michael | title = Ribbon Around The Pentagon | url = https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost_historical/doc/138227300.html | journal = Washington Post | date= September 12, 1984 |page = B1 | accessdate=2014-03-08 | subscription = yes}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last = Boscov | first = Rema | title= Three Years of Peace Work | url = https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost_historical/doc/138625864.html | journal = Washington Post | date = July 16, 1985 | page = C7 | accessdate=2014-03-08 | subscription = yes}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last = Hyer | first = Marjorie | title = Prayers for Peace Interwoven | url = https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost_historical/doc/138619411.html | date = July 27, 1985 | page = G10| accessdate = 2014-03-08 | subscription = yes}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | title = Where to See Ribbon Segments | url = https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost_historical/doc/138595982.html | journal = Washington Post | date = July 27, 1985 | page = G10 | accessdate = 2014-03-08 | subscription = yes}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last = Weil | first = Martin | title= Police Say 15-Mile Peace Ribbon Won't Tie Up D.C. Traffic | url = https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost_historical/doc/138611097.html | journal = Washington Post | date = August 3, 1985 |page = B1 | accessdate = 2014-03-08 | subscription = yes}}</ref> and national publications such as ''[[McCall's]]'' (Gittelson 1985), ''[[Mother Jones (magazine)|Mother Jones]]'' (Robinson 1985), ''[[People (American magazine)|People]]'' (Grogan<ref name="Grogan"/> and Chandler 1985), and ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]'' magazine (L. Davis 1985). Coverage appeared in ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine (Pierce 1985)<ref>{{cite journal | last = Pierce | first = Kenneth M.| title = This Could Be Ground Zero: Throngs recall the Bomb | url = http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,1050464,00.html | journal = Time Magazine | date = August 19, 1985 | volume = 126 | issue = 7| accessdate = 2014-02-25 | subscription = yes}}</ref> and on the front page of the ''[[Washington Post]]'' (Saperstein 1985,<ref>{{cite journal | last = Saperstrin | first = Saundra | title = Peace Lovers Have a Banner Day | url = https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost_historical/doc/138615604.html | journal = Washington Post | date = August 5, 1985 | pages = A1–A2 | accessdate=2014-02-25 | subscription = yes}}</ref> Kastor 1985,<ref>{{cite journal | last = Kastor | first = Elizabeth | title = The Images That Made Up The Ribbon The Ribbon | url = https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost_historical/doc/138613699.html | journal = Washington Post | date = August 5, 1985 | pages = B1–B2 | accessdate = 2014-02-25 | subscription = yes}}</ref> McGrory 1985<ref>{{cite journal | last = McGrory | first = Mary | title = The Woman Who's Needling Warmakers | url = https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost_historical/doc/138554428.html | journal = Washington Post | date = August 4, 1985 | pages = B1–B2 | accessdate=2014-02-25 | subscription = yes}}</ref>) after the event. The Ribbon was covered by major radio and television networks. Merritt appeared on ''[[Good Morning America]]'' in June and August (before the event) and again in November 1985.{{sfn|Pershing|1996|p=160}}
[[File:California Banner on Mall.jpg|thumb|Californians contributed over 3,000 panels.]] Panels were received from contributors in every state in the United States. Every state and many towns and organizations held Ribbon joining events. Panels were received from all over the world, including Russia, England, Germany, New Zealand, Italy, Canada, Australia, the Netherlands, and Puerto Rico.<ref name="The Ribbon Starts Here">{{cite AV media | title = The Ribbon Starts Here |url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=c5FiK79mvYk| accessdate = 2018-01-08}}</ref> A group of women with [[Church Women United]] led a grassroots effort around the country, making panels and assisting with preparations in Washington. Their newsletter, which was sent to a half a million members of the [[Catholic Church]], the [[Russian Orthodox Church in America]], the [[Salvation Army]], the [[Quakers]], and 29 other [[Christian denominations]], provided information on how to construct the panels. More than 3,000 Ribbon panels were contributed by this group.<ref name="Pentagon Ceremony"/><ref name="Janzen">{{cite journal | last = Janzen | first = Victoria | title = Kansans and The Peace Ribbon Around the Pentagon in the 1980s | url = http://archive.bethelks.edu/ml/issue/vol-64/article/kansans-and-the-peace-ribbon-around-the-pentagon-i/ | journal = Mennonite Life | date = Summer 2010 | volume = 64 | accessdate = 2014-06-11}}</ref><ref name="Hartman">{{cite journal | title = Biography of Annabel Hartman | url = http://www.indianahistory.org/our-collections/collection-guides/annabel-hartman-papers-1981-1990.pdf| publisher = Indiana Historical Society | date = March 31, 2003 | accessdate = 2014-02-25}}</ref> The California delegation contributed over 3,000 panels for the Ribbon event. In 1984, they created a display of panels that surrounded [[Lake Merritt]] in [[Oakland]].{{sfn|Pershing|1996|p=93}} The California group also sent panels to Hiroshima for a Ribbon event that was going to surround the at the [[Hiroshima Peace Memorial]] on the same day as the Pentagon event.<ref name="Steele">{{cite journal | last = Steele | first = R. David | title = The World Is Comin' to a Start – Peace Ribbon Brings Hope and Community | journal = Sequoia | publisher = Northern California Ecumenical Council | date = October 1985 | page = 3}}</ref>
Marie Dennis Grosso, Joan Urbanczyk, and Margaret Schellenberg of the Center for a New Creation (a peace group in [[Arlington County, Virginia|Arlington]], Virginia) coordinated the Washington event. The center concentrated on peacemaking, poverty and economic justice, human rights, and women's issues.{{sfn|Pershing|1996|p=103}} [[Betty Bumpers]], an advocate for world peace and wife of former U.S. Senator and Governor of Arkansas [[Dale Bumpers]], also worked on preparations for the Washington event with her group Peace Links, a national nonpartisan organization of women who oppose the nuclear arms buildup.{<ref name="Rowley">{{cite web | last = Rowley | first = James | title = Group Plans To Stretch 'Peace Ribbon' From Pentagon To Capitol Hill | url = http://www.apnewsarchive.com/1985/Group-Plans-To-Stretch-Peace-Ribbon-From-Pentagon-To-Capitol-Hill/id-4ba9b8b731d43f111f107bcc56e9a6a8 | agency = Associated Press | date = August 2, 1985 | accessdate = 2014-05-10}}</ref>{{sfn|Pershing|1996|p=149}} Organizers planned a {{convert|10|to|15|mi|km|adj=on}} route through Washington D.C., and met with various police authorities and the [[National Park Service]] to obtain the required permits. Security was of utmost importance; the course from Virginia into Washington travelled past some of the most important buildings and monuments in the country. Forty-nine churches and one senior's center in the Washington area hosted individual state delegations and participants. The churches held a reception for attendees and provided bag lunches, lodging, and transportation. Host churches also displayed panels.{{sfn|Pershing|1996|pp=103–104}}<ref name="Wilcox"/>
== Events in Washington == [[File:Washing National Cathedral.jpg|thumb|Each of the 2,500 pews in the cathedral was covered with a panel.]] [[File:The Ribbon Starts Here.jpg|thumb|Assembly of the Ribbon gets underway at the [[United States Capitol]], Washington, D.C.]] The interfaith service for peace, held on August 3 at the [[Washington National Cathedral]], was attended by 5,000 people. Cathedral staff reported that it was the second-largest crowd ever hosted in the building.{{sfn|Pershing|1996|p=150}} Over 4,000 panels were on display during the service. Each pew was decorated, and additional Ribbons were draped and tied in various locations around the building. Twenty bagpipers in Highland dress led a procession of 200 people carrying Ribbons into the cathedral. The service also included dancing, meditation, and a performance by the [[Howard University]] Gospel Choir.<ref name="Steele"/><ref name="Ribbon News Letter">{{cite journal | title= 'Ribbon' Documentary| journal = The Ribbon Newsletter | volume = October 1985 }}</ref> Survivors of the Hiroshima and Nagasaki bombings were in attendance both at the church service and during The Ribbon event the next day.
When all 27,000 individual panels were joined together on August 4, it created a ribbon {{convert|18|mi}} long.<ref name="Weil" /> Don Wilcox of ''The Craft Report'' described it as "the largest collaborative craft event in American history".<ref name="Wilcox"/> The Ribbon wrapped around the Pentagon building, through the Pentagon parking lot, down the foot paths alongside the [[Jefferson Davis Highway]] and [[Washington Boulevard (Arlington)|Washington Boulevard]], crossed the [[Potomac River]] into Washington D.C. at the [[Arlington Memorial Bridge]], and travelled into the [[National Mall]] area. The Ribbon then went past the [[Lincoln Memorial]], along the south side of the [[Lincoln Memorial Reflecting Pool]], continuing east along the National Mall, and around the U.S.[[United States Capitol|Capitol Building]]. It then turned west along the north side of the National Mall, went around the Ellipse by the White House, passed the Lincoln Memorial, crossed the Potomac River again and returned to the Pentagon. When the chain of panels was completed, hundreds of balloons were released near the Lincoln Memorial. The entire route was lined with people, and crowds gathered at the three designated speaking areas (the Pentagon, the Lincoln Memorial, and the Capitol). Singers, including [[Pete Seeger]] and [[Tom Chapin]], rotated between the three stage areas, performing anti-war songs.<ref name="Sanders">{{cite journal | last = Sanders | first = Steve | title = 'Peace Ribbon' Tied Around The Capitol | url = http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1985-08-05/news/8502200974_1_chicago-peace-museum-justine-merritt-lincoln-memorial | journal = Chicago Tribune | date = August 5, 1985 | accessdate = 2014-06-28}}</ref>{{sfn|Pershing|1996|p=154}} Newspapers estimated a total attendance of 30,000 to 100,000 people.{{citation needed|date=June 2014}}
Video filming was done by numerous individuals, and professional television video personnel from New York and Washington, D.C., who donated their time and equipment to create a documentary about the event. The documentary film ''The Ribbon Starts Here'',<ref name="The Ribbon Starts Here"/> was produced by Academy Award-winning film maker [[Nigel Noble]], and directed by Nigel Noble and Hilary Raff Lindsay; Nobel Enterprises. The video was released in 1988.<ref name="Wilcox"/>{{sfn|Pershing|1996|p=292}}
== Subsequent events == After August 4, state coordinators returned home with their Ribbon panels, which were then displayed in libraries, schools, and museums, and used in parades and events.<ref name="Weil">{{cite journal | last = Weil | first = Dorothy | title = Peace Packages Around The Pentagon | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=Wh8DAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA155&lpg=PA155&dq=picture+#v=onepage&q=picture&f=false | journal = Cincinnati Magazine | date = November 1986 | pages = 155–157 | accessdate = 2014-06-28}}</ref>{{sfn|Pershing|1996|p={{page needed|date=June 2014}} }} Historical societies and universities now house historical information about the Ribbon and archival collections of panels.<ref name="Hartman"/><ref>{{cite web | title = Peace Ribbon Project Northwest Ohio | url = http://www2.bgsu.edu/colleges/library/cac/ms/page45281.html |publisher = Center for Archival Collections, Bowling Green State University | accessdate = 2014-06-28}}</ref> Some of the Ribbons and panels were selected as gallery pieces, and are on display in [[The Peace Museum]] in Chicago. Sixty Ribbons were selected by the [[Smithsonian Institution]] for its political history collection, and others were given to the [[United Nations]].<ref name="Pentagon Ceremony"/><ref name="Sanders"/><ref>{{cite journal | last = Fanning | first = Robbie | title = After the Ribbon | journal = Threads Magazine | date = December 1985 – January 1986 | page = 14}}</ref> The Texas Women's University in [[Denton, Texas]] hosts a major collection of panels and documentation. Panels were also sent to the National Textile Museum.<ref name= "Ribbon News Letter"/>
[[File:RibbonPopeEditWiki4.25.jpg|thumb|left |Pope John Paul II, Michele Peppers and Justine Merritt at the Vatican, Rome, October 17, 2001]]
The Ribbon evolved into The Ribbon International in the late 1980s, and became a United Nations Non Governmental Organization in 1991.<ref name="The Ribbon International"/> Ribbon events can be held for special designated days such as the [[International Day of Peace]] (September 21), [[Earth Day]] (April 21), special prayer days or other events. Any individual or group can create a panel for a Ribbon, start a Ribbon in their community, or give a panel as a gift to someone who is engaged in promoting peace, environmental causes, or disarmament.<ref name="Peppers 14"/>
New panels continue to be created for display at various environmental and peace events. Ribbons have been given to the [[New York City Council]], Russian President [[Mikhail Gorbachev]], Indian Prime Minister [[Rajiv Gandhi]], and [[Pope John Paul II]].<ref>{{cite journal | last = Palmer | first = Susan | title = Peace Winds Like a Ribbon |url = https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/registerguard/doc/377698479.html | journal = Eugene Register-Guard | date = May 14, 2005 |page = D1 | accessdate = 2014-02-25 | subscription = yes}}</ref> Panels from the Ribbon were displayed at the [[United Nations Decade for Women]] international conference in [[Nairobi]] in 1985, and others were used by members of Women for a Meaningful Summit at their demonstration at the [[Geneva Summit (1985)]]. Ribbons were used at peace demonstrations at the [[Nevada Nuclear Test Site]], and the Horse Creek Missile Silo near [[Cheyenne, Wyoming]], and the [[Great Peace March for Global Nuclear Disarmament]] in 1986.{{sfn|Pershing|1996|p=264}}
[[File:Ribbon Around the ABomb Memorial, Hiroshima.jpg|thumb|Ribbons surround the [[Hiroshima Peace Memorial]] ending the conference "Building a Just and Sustainable Peace." April 3, 2006.]] In 2000, with the help of Betty Bumpers and her group Peace Links, the Ribbon International United Nations Non Governmental Committee gave each U.S. congressional leader a Ribbon for the United Nations [[International Year for the Culture of Peace]], and for the [[International Decade for the Promotion of a Culture of Peace and Non-Violence for the Children of the World]], 2001–2010. Some congressional leaders displayed the Ribbon in their offices.<ref>{{cite journal | editor1-last = Kroyer | editor1-first = Frank | title = Presentation of US, Long Island Ribbon panel to Cuban Church | journal = International Teacher | date = July 2001 | page = 30 | issn = 1396-8580}}</ref>
Every year the municipality and city of [[Lugansk]], [[Ukraine]] takes part in the Ribbon project.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.theribboninternational.org/town-activity.html | publisher = The Ribbon International | title = Town Activity | accessdate=2014-06-28}}</ref> Annual events are held in Marion and Gas City, [[Indiana]], and in [[Lake Havasu]], [[Arizona]], where people create Ribbons and hold a Ribbon event for [[United Nations Day]] (October 24) or other peace related days.<ref>{{cite journal | title = Twin Cities United To The World Through Ribbons of Peace | journal = Twin City Journal-Reporter | location = Gas City, IN | date = October 9, 1996 | page = 4}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last = Reynolds | first = Mary | title = Sewing Up the Project | journal = Today's News-Herald | location = Lake Havasu, AZ | volume = 35 | issue = 189 | date = September 26, 2000 | page = 1}}</ref>
[[File:Mayors For Peace NYC.jpg|left|thumb|The first Nuclear Weapons Abolition Day. New York City, April 28, 2004]] In Japan, the city of Hiroshima includes Ribbons and prayers for peace in their annual commemoration of the nuclear bombing.<ref>{{cite journal | editor1-last = Roshan | editor1-first = Sorosh | title = Peace Ribbons at Atomic Bomb Dome | journal = International Health Awareness Network | date = Spring 2006 | page = 2}}</ref> In [[Israel]], [[Interns for Peace]] works with Israeli and Palestinian youth to stage Ribbon events, joining them together at the [[Gaza Strip]].<ref>{{cite journal | last = Hevesi | first = Dennis | title = Rabbi Bruce M. Cohen, Is Dead at 65; Worked to Promote Peace | journal = New York Times | date = August 8, 2010 | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/09/world/middleeast/09cohen.html?_r=0 | accessdate = 2014-06-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media | title = Zap To Peace | date = 1995 | publisher = [[Israel Broadcasting Authority]]}}</ref> In [[New Zealand]], people joined Ribbons around the United States and Russian Embassies in [[Wellington]].<ref>{{cite journal | journal = Peacemeal | title = The Ribbon Embassies Link Up | issue = 13 |date = November–December 1986 | location = Wellington, New Zealand}}</ref> From 2002 to 2012, the Ribbon committee in New York City annually joined Ribbons, starting at the [[United Nations Headquarters]] and travelling to the [[World Trade Center site|World Trade Center]].<ref>{{cite journal | last = Bussell | first = Lynne | title = 2006 Ribbon Joining at the United Nations WTC | journal = Church Women News | volume = 1 | issue = 3 | date = June 2006 | page = 8}}</ref> After the [[September 11 attacks]], Merritt called the Ribbon the "Ribbon of Tangible Hope". She wanted to create a Ribbon long enough to stretch from the United Nations to the World Trade Center Memorial site and to a Muslim shrine.<ref>{{cite news | last = Palmer | first = Susan | title = Activist Who Inspired a Global Peace Project Dies in Eugene at 84 | journal = Eugene Register-Guard | date = January 28, 2009}}</ref>
The Ribbon Committee worked with New York City Council on Nuclear Weapons Abolition Day, held April 28, 2004.<ref>{{cite web | title = Nuclear Abolition Day | url = http://www.nuclearabolition.info/ | accessdate = 2014-05-10}}</ref> Over the years, Church Women United has wrapped the Ribbon around numerous sites. The group held a peace litany joining "the Ribbon of Tangible Hope" in the state capital building in [[Oklahoma City]] on the fifteenth anniversary of the [[Oklahoma City bombing]].<ref>{{cite web | publisher = State of Oklahoma | title = A resolution honoring the victims of the Oklahoma City bombing; thanking Church Women United for their commemoration; and directing distribution | work = Enrolled Senate Resolution No. 111 | author = Anderson| date = April 15, 2010 | url = https://www.sos.ok.gov/documents/legislation/52nd/2010/2R/SR/111.pdf | accessdate = 2014-06-28 | format = PDF|display-authors=etal}}</ref> {{-}}
